I am probably out of line because I did not make this recipe, but I regularly make one that is amazingly similar. The only difference is that six whole eggs are whisked in a bowl while the chocolate is melting, and then added at once. The resulting texture is a very dense but silky smooth chocolate, and the top is fairly uniform. I top mine with chocolate ganache which covers any imperfections, and this ALWAYS gets rave reviews!

Rating: 4
We used 1/2 bittersweet (60% cacao) and 1/2 semisweet (both Ghirardelli). Made the entire quantity of glaze but applied only the first step - nearly a 1/8" thick coating. I couldn't wait to try it, so I had some after cooling in the fridge for only 2 hours. My first opinion was that it was just ok. My second tasting 18 hours later totally changed my opinion. The cake was much denser and consistently moist - much closer to what we have had in restaurants. I highly recommend removing all of the crusty top and sides - the crunchiness throws off the smooth texture. Add some homemade whipped cream and raspberry sauce and you have an amazing dessert. Definitely worth making again.

Rating: 0
To Cook 07/17/09 -- Splenda or any other sugar substitute won't really work in this sense, because the eggs need the chemical structure of sugar to whip properly. If you add Splenda you won't get the volume in the whites/yolks, and then you won't get volume in the cake itself, it'll be super dense and heavy. Hope that helps!

