Rating: 4
to get some height, this the trick, got it from Julia Childs I think or that Jacques guy. Take the first slab on your spatula and mix it well with the chocolate mixture. The rest fold in gently, DO NOT overmix! The 1st slab will equalize the consistency so that the folding happens with ease. I also cover the pan with foil to avoid burning of the edges. I use either Valhrona or Green & Blacks Organic and get an AAAA+++++ cake everytime! Email me at maldades04@yahoo.com if you need tips on this recipe, I have made it over a hundred times, maybe a thousand, lol! Enjoy, this is my favorite dessert of all!

Rating: 4
Rich, decadent, and truly a chocolate lover's dream. Followed the recipe as written, except baked for only 41 minutes (used an oven thermometer and the toothpick came out clean at 41 minutes). I had no problems with the cake being dry or having uneven sides. Because the cake is sooo rich, I highly recommend serving small slices with vanilla icecream, raspberry coulis and fresh raspberries. Excellent recipe...your family and friends will love you even more for making this. This is a definite keeper.

Rating: 4
I've made this recipe many times. When I am more careful about folding in the egg whites (and not breaking them), I have a higher cake - it always settles down to just over an inch though. That's the nature of the cake. Because of the settling, the sides are always uneven, so the glaze it needed to make it look presentable. A huge hit whenever I cook it. Crucial to use good chocolate too, it makes a difference in cooking and taste.

Rating: 4
I am a novice baker and this was one of my first cakes. I chose it because my husband absolutely loves flourless chocolate cakes, and with all of the wonderful restaurants and bakeries here in New York City, he certainly has tasted excellent flourless chocolate cakes. This cake tasted delicious, and my husband said it was on par, if not better, than the best flourless chocolate cake he has ever had. The consistency and tase were just perfect. I will definitely make it again for the two of us. However, I had two problems, and maybe someone can help me solve them for next time. First, the cake came out very thin, only about an inch high. Also, the sides of the cake were not smooth, so they looked messy (I did not cover it with any glaze, I just sprinkled the top with confectioner's sugar). I really do not know why these two things happened. But, as I said, I am just a beginner, and this tasted like a pro baked it, so I love this recipe and will make it again.

