Rating: 4
This cake has become a famous dessert in my house.I find that the people whos had problems with it its because they didnt read it CAREFULLY.Use bittersweet chocolate as the recipe directs and the whites have to be beaten with sugar so they dont dry and remain flexible.Be careful with your oven, it may take a little bit more baking.Its so easy and so delicious!!!!

Rating: 4
Ohmygoodness this is a wonderful cake!! I was a little surprised by it, but not at all disappointed. It rose quite high while baking, but turned out that the height was all crust and inside was a heavy layer of dense, moist chocolate (yay!) Instead of pushing the crust down, we just cut it level and ate the crust crumbs... :) I used Ghiradelli bittersweet chocolate for both the cake and the glaze and it was perfect! I must say I'm the laziest cook in the world, so I changed the order of a couple things... I beat the egg whites first and then the yolks, so I didn't have to be so careful about the beaters being clean, I added all the sugar before beating instead of half-way through (on the whites) and I didn't do the thirds for folding, just a little to lighten and then dump it back in. I might have had a lighter cake had I followed the instructions, but dense was my goal and I loved it! I didn't find the glaze instructions too bad, either and I was really pretty impressed how well the glaze set up at room temperature (I didn't want to chill it, since the humidity around here tends to leave a bit of water on anything coming out of the fridge). I did use light corn syrup instead of dark (the lid was stuck on the dark!) -- I don't know what kind of difference that would make... Now if only I knew more people who weren't on diets I could arrange to eat this once a week! *sigh*

Rating: 2
I carefully followed recipe directions, using Callebaut chocolate, and tested it for doneness after baking it 50 min. as the recipe stated, but it was still liquid in the center (under a crusted top), as it was at 55 minutes. At 1 hour, the cake tester showed very moist crumbs so I removed it from the oven to cool. The cake was anticlimatic, being definitely on the dry side when served. The glaze was delicious, and the cake flavor good, but the texture disappointing. I may try it one more time, baking it only 50 minutes but allowing it to cool partially in the oven, as when baking a cheesecake. This might let it set up sufficiently without drying out, but if the outcome is no better the second time, this recipe will be history. The flavor was excellent, VERY chocolatey, but it needed more moistness to please the non-chocoholics, even served with vanilla ice cream.

